📌 Challenge

Today's task focused on managing multiple Git remotes within an existing repository.

The development team introduced a new remote repository for the project, requiring the local repository to be updated with an additional remote. After configuring the new remote, a new project file needed to be committed and pushed to the new destination.

🛠️ Objectives
Add a new Git remote (dev_news)
Point the remote to a different repository
Copy a new file into the repository
Stage and commit the changes
Push the master branch to the new remote
📂 Repository Structure
Storage Server
│
├── Existing Remote
│      /opt/news.git
│
├── New Remote
│      /opt/xfusioncorp_news.git
│
└── Local Repository
       /usr/src/kodekloudrepos/news
🔧 Commands Used
cd /usr/src/kodekloudrepos/news

git remote add dev_news /opt/xfusioncorp_news.git

cp /tmp/index.html .

git add index.html

git commit -m "Add index.html"

git push dev_news master
✅ Verification

Verify the configured remotes:

git remote -v

Expected output:

origin      /opt/news.git
dev_news    /opt/xfusioncorp_news.git

Verify the latest commit:

git log --oneline -1
🧠 Key Concepts Learned
Git repositories can have multiple remotes.
A remote is simply another repository your local project can communicate with.
Developers can push the same codebase to multiple repositories.
git remote add allows additional destinations without affecting the existing origin.
Git separates local commits from remote repositories, giving developers flexibility over where changes are pushed.
🌍 Real-World DevOps Scenario

Organizations often maintain multiple Git remotes for different purposes:

Internal development repository
Customer-facing repository
Backup repository
Migration repository
Open-source mirror

Instead of cloning the project multiple times, engineers configure additional remotes and selectively push changes where needed.

